{% extends "demo.html.j2" %}

{% set deg = card_data.degradation_table %}
{% set reg = card_data.registry_snippet %}
{% set headline = card_data.headline %}
{% set alpha_r = deg.alpha_estimation.R %}
{% set alpha_e = deg.alpha_estimation.E %}
{% set false_attribution = headline.r_tier_false_attribution %}

{% block head_extra %}
<link rel="stylesheet" href="{{ asset_base | default('') }}assets/pages/x1.css">
{% endblock %}

{% block demo_content %}
<section class="atlas-intro">
  <p class="atlas-headline">
    How much data until a metric means anything? At a reference effect,
    <strong>only the E-tier shrinkage posterior reaches {{ "%.0f"|format(headline.reference.target_power * 100) }}% power within a {{ headline.reference.max_months // 12 }}-year record</strong>:
    {{ "%.1f"|format(headline.e_tier.power * 100) }}% at {{ headline.e_tier.threshold_months }} months,
    with Wilson 95% half-width &plusmn;{{ "%.1f"|format(headline.e_tier.wilson.half_width * 100) }} percentage points.
    Frequentist tests never clear the bar in the measured range.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="tearsheet-panel">
  <h2 class="tearsheet-panel__title">What this exhibit shows</h2>
  <p class="tearsheet-note"><strong>What you are looking at.</strong>
  Three panels ask the same question &mdash; how many months of track record does a
  skill test need before it is reliable &mdash; at three known skill levels (realized
  IR {{ "%.2f"|format(card_data.power_curves[0].realized_ir) }}, {{ "%.2f"|format(card_data.power_curves[1].realized_ir) }}, and {{ "%.2f"|format(card_data.power_curves[2].realized_ir) }}). These curves are the returns-only (R-tier) slice: the
  cohort-informed shrinkage posterior climbs fastest but still tops out just below
  the {{ "%.0f"|format(headline.reference.target_power * 100) }}% point gate at the middle effect
  ({{ "%.1f"|format(headline.r_tier.power * 100) }}%, or {{ "%.3f"|format(headline.r_tier.power) }}, at T={{ headline.reference.max_months }}).
  Its Wilson 95% interval is
  {{ "%.1f"|format(headline.r_tier.wilson.lo * 100) }}%&ndash;{{ "%.1f"|format(headline.r_tier.wilson.hi * 100) }}%,
  which spans the {{ "%.0f"|format(headline.reference.target_power * 100) }}% bar; the gate decision remains based on the {{ "%.3f"|format(headline.r_tier.power) }} point estimate.
  It fires {{ "%.1f"|format(false_attribution.power * 100) }}% of the
  time when there is no skill at all (its IC={{ "%g"|format(false_attribution.ic) }} false-alarm rate at T={{ false_attribution.months }}). Pinning betas at
  tier E is what pushes the posterior over the bar within a {{ headline.reference.max_months // 12 }}-year record &mdash;
  which is the atlas headline. The degradation table below reads the same effect at a fixed cell (T={{ deg.T }},
  IC={{ "%.2f"|format(deg.ic) }}): alpha estimation lifts from {{ "%.1f"|format(alpha_r.power * 100) }}% power at returns-tier to {{ "%.1f"|format(alpha_e.power * 100) }}% at
  exposure-tier, and every number is {{ card_data.meta.n_reps }}-manager simulator output, illustrative
  and uncalibrated.</p>
  <p class="tearsheet-note"><strong>How to read it.</strong></p>
  <ul class="tearsheet-note">
    <li><strong>Two lines per panel</strong> &mdash; the OLS <em>t</em>-test and the
    shrinkage posterior, plotted as detection rate (power) against sample length
    <em>T</em> in months.</li>
    <li><strong>Dashed horizontal line</strong> &mdash; the {{ "%.0f"|format(headline.reference.target_power * 100) }}% power bar; where a
    curve crosses it is the tenure at which that metric becomes reliable.</li>
    <li><strong>Amber poster label</strong> &mdash; the posterior's false-alarm price
    ({{ "%.1f"|format(false_attribution.power * 100) }}% false-attribution at IC={{ "%g"|format(false_attribution.ic) }}), the cost of borrowing strength across a cohort.</li>
    <li><strong>Degradation table</strong> &mdash; power (and RMSE where it applies)
    for each analytic by transparency tier; the tier gap is what visibility buys.</li>
    <li><strong>Registry rows</strong> &mdash; each metric's gate; a null threshold
    prints as "no tenure in the measured range suffices," meaning it never clears {{ "%.0f"|format(headline.reference.target_power * 100) }}%
    power here.</li>
  </ul>
  <p class="tearsheet-note">The full methodology &mdash; with the math and a reference
  implementation &mdash; is in the
  <a href="{{ asset_base | default('') }}specs/{{ card.id }}.html">method spec</a>.</p>
</section>

<section class="tearsheet-panel">
  <h2 class="tearsheet-panel__title">Exhibit 1 &mdash; power curves: OLS t-test vs shrinkage posterior</h2>
  <p class="atlas-poster-label">
    cohort-informed; {{ "%.1f"|format(false_attribution.power * 100) }}% false-attribution at IC={{ "%g"|format(false_attribution.ic) }} &mdash; the price of borrowing strength
  </p>
  <div class="atlas-curves">
    {% for curve in card_data.power_curves %}
    <figure class="atlas-curve">
      <svg class="x1-powercurve" viewBox="0 0 100 44" preserveAspectRatio="none"
           role="img" aria-label="Power vs sample length"
           data-t="{{ curve.T | join(',') }}"
           data-ols="{{ curve.ols_ttest | join(',') }}"
           data-ols-lo="{{ curve.ols_ttest_wilson | map(attribute='lo') | join(',') }}"
           data-ols-hi="{{ curve.ols_ttest_wilson | map(attribute='hi') | join(',') }}"
           data-posterior="{{ curve.posterior | join(',') }}"
           data-posterior-lo="{{ curve.posterior_wilson | map(attribute='lo') | join(',') }}"
           data-posterior-hi="{{ curve.posterior_wilson | map(attribute='hi') | join(',') }}"></svg>
      <figcaption class="atlas-curve__cap">
        realized IR {{ "%.2f"|format(curve.realized_ir) }}
        <span class="atlas-curve__legend">
          <span class="atlas-legend atlas-legend--ols">OLS t-test</span>
          <span class="atlas-legend atlas-legend--posterior">posterior</span>
        </span>
      </figcaption>
    </figure>
    {% endfor %}
  </div>
  <p class="tearsheet-note">Dashed line marks the {{ "%.0f"|format(headline.reference.target_power * 100) }}% power threshold; x-axis is T (months),
  {{ card_data.power_curves[0].T[0] }} to {{ card_data.power_curves[0].T[-1] }}. Shaded envelopes show Wilson 95% intervals.</p>
</section>

<section class="tearsheet-panel">
  <h2 class="tearsheet-panel__title">Exhibit 2 &mdash; tier degradation (T={{ deg.T }}, IC={{ "%.2f"|format(deg.ic) }})</h2>
  <table class="atlas-degradation">
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Analytic</th><th>Tier</th><th>Power</th><th>Monte Carlo uncertainty</th><th>RMSE</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Alpha estimation</td><td>R</td><td>{{ "%.1f"|format(deg.alpha_estimation.R.power * 100) }}%</td><td>Wilson 95% &plusmn;{{ "%.1f"|format(deg.alpha_estimation.R.wilson.half_width * 100) }} pp</td><td>{{ "%.4f"|format(deg.alpha_estimation.R.rmse) }}</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Alpha estimation</td><td>E</td><td>{{ "%.1f"|format(deg.alpha_estimation.E.power * 100) }}%</td><td>Wilson 95% &plusmn;{{ "%.1f"|format(deg.alpha_estimation.E.wilson.half_width * 100) }} pp</td><td>{{ "%.4f"|format(deg.alpha_estimation.E.rmse) }}</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Hit rate</td><td>P</td><td>{{ "%.1f"|format(deg.hit_rate_P.power * 100) }}%</td><td>Wilson 95% &plusmn;{{ "%.1f"|format(deg.hit_rate_P.wilson.half_width * 100) }} pp</td><td>&mdash;</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Sizing skill</td><td>P</td><td>{{ "%.1f"|format(deg.sizing_skill_P.power * 100) }}%</td><td>Wilson 95% &plusmn;{{ "%.1f"|format(deg.sizing_skill_P.wilson.half_width * 100) }} pp</td><td>&mdash;</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Drift detection</td><td>E vs R</td><td colspan="3">{{ deg.drift_detection }}</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
</section>

<section class="tearsheet-panel">
  <h2 class="tearsheet-panel__title">Exhibit 3 &mdash; PowerGate registry (sampler)</h2>
  <p class="tearsheet-note">The machine-readable thresholds file every gated card consumes.
  A null threshold means the metric never reaches {{ "%.0f"|format(headline.reference.target_power * 100) }}% power in the measured range.</p>
  <dl class="x1-registry">
    {% for name, m in reg.metrics.items() %}
    <div class="x1-registry__row">
      <dt class="x1-registry__metric">{{ name }}</dt>
      <dd class="x1-registry__body">
        <span class="x1-registry__field">min tier {{ m.min_tier }}</span>
        <span class="x1-registry__field">gate: {{ m.gate_quantity }}</span>
        <span class="x1-registry__field">effect: {{ m.effect }}</span>
        <span class="x1-registry__field">size {{ "%.2f"|format(m.size) }}, power@thr {{ "%.2f"|format(m.power_at_threshold) }}</span>
        <span class="x1-registry__threshold">
          {% if m.threshold is none %}no tenure in the measured range suffices{% else %}threshold {{ m.threshold }} {{ m.gate_quantity }}{% endif %}
        </span>
      </dd>
    </div>
    {% endfor %}
  </dl>
</section>
{% endblock %}

{% block methodology %}
<p>The simulator emits all three transparency tiers of the same known ground truth, so
every metric is scored against the truth at every tier and sample size. Power =
P(detect | effect present); size = P(detect | IC = 0); the IC=0 column is the
false-alarm rate, not filler. Each power number carries its own Wilson 95%
half-width (this sampler runs 500 managers per cell; atlas vol.&nbsp;1 raises
that to &ge;1,000).</p>
<p>The shrinkage posterior borrows strength across a strategy cohort, buying power at
short tenures &mdash; at the cost of {{ "%.1f"|format(false_attribution.power * 100) }}% false-attribution at IC={{ "%g"|format(false_attribution.ic) }}. That is the price
of borrowing strength, stated plainly rather than hidden.</p>
{% endblock %}

{% block body_scripts %}
<script src="{{ asset_base | default('') }}assets/x1-atlas.js"></script>
{% endblock %}
